  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency lifesaving WASH  support for vulnerable IDPs in Gongulong, Jere LGA</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The ongoing OAG insurgency continues to show no sign of ending with continuous movement of IDPs across Borno State. Gongulong host community is providing residency to 9,037 IDPs according to IOM DTM Round 28. Gongulong is located in Jere LGA. According to IOM, comparison between DTM Round 27 amp 28, this LGA experienced an increase of 1,950 IDPs. The presence of IDPs in host communities have placed huge pressure on available community assets including water points, latrines, land for farming, etc. With restriction on movement beyond secured perimeter, the population is heavily dependent on humanitarian assistance for survival. An assessment conducted by ZOA in September amp October 2019 shows that the population is in urgent need of water, latrines and hygiene kits. Rehabilitation of damaged latrines and bathing shelters will reduce environmental hazards and provide dignity to IDPs and host community population through safe access to WASH facilities. There is increased open defecation due to more dysfunctional latrines some of these latrines were constructed by NHF funding other different projects few months back but are now damaged or dysfunctional.  There is a need for hygiene promotion. Gongulong is among the communities which are hot spots of cholera outbreak. The community experienced also flooding in 2019. Mainstreaming cholera preparation and prevention would reduce the exposure of the population to cholera. Targeting children through separate hygiene sessions as well as WASH in schools would contribute to reduction in child mortality. Providing hygiene kits, especially soaps will provide a good basis to application of the hygiene and sanitation lessons. This project will also target the rehabilitation and maintenance of WASH facilities constructed with NHF funding in Gongulong.</narrative>
  </description>
